 KEG president Churchill Otieno told the press on Thursday that measures have been put in place since then to ensure that debates adhere to the principles of fairness, integrity, independence, and accountability. In collaboration with Kenyan newsrooms, Churchill asserted that coverage of the proceedings will "have a professional platform managed by professionals." "This year the media has gone to great lengths to make sure that the debates is a special platform who only interest is to enable Kenyans to access credible and accurate information from the candidates so as to enable them to make choices when August 9 comes," Churchill said. "We have also put together a panel of editors comprising editors in chief and managing editors from key media houses in Kenya. As they do that they stand on very clear pillars, the ethics of journalism in Kenya but more importantly they are keen to ensure that every candidate gets the coverage that they deserve and makes sure that their manifestos and the issues that they stand on can get to Kenyans.," At the same time, the committee stated that the debates will take place in July as planned, and that dates and other details, such as how Kenyans can participate, will be announced in due time. The Kenya Editors' Guild, the Media Owners Association, and the Kenya Media Council collaborate to form the Presidential Debates Secretariat. During election years, the Secretariat hosts Presidential Debates, which it has done for the past ten years in 2013 and 2017.